<ComingSoonRoomLayout
  room="founders"
  title="Founders' Cabinet"
  subtitle="The 1785 framers and the line of advocates who followed."
  sourceId="coming-soon-founders"
>
  <p>
    The Founders' Cabinet honors the men and women who built the school
    trust and the long line of advocates who carried it forward through the
    centuries. The room begins with the Confederation Congress committee of
    1785 — Thomas Jefferson, William Grayson, Hugh Williamson, and the
    lesser-known members who voted the Land Ordinance into being. Their
    portraits and biographies sit in cases along one wall. Across from
    them, the line of advocates who came after — the territorial delegates
    who fought for fair Enabling Act terms, the state superintendents who
    insisted on accounting, the federal judges who built the doctrine, the
    modern beneficiary-rights litigators, and Margaret Bird, who has done
    more than anyone alive to keep the school-trust conversation honest.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Why this room matters.</strong> Institutions that last across
    centuries do so because individual people, generation after generation,
    tend them. The school trust is now in the hands of a generation that
    has mostly forgotten it exists. The Founders' Cabinet is the room that
    names the people who carried it this far, so the next generation knows
    the chain they're being asked to join.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>What they didn't foresee.</strong> A small alcove at the back of
    the cabinet will document the failure modes the 1785 framers didn't
    anticipate — railroad land grants, mineral severance, the federal
    mineral leasing acts, sovereign-immunity defenses. A library is honest
    about its founders' limits.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>Being planned.</strong> Jefferson and Margaret first.
  </p>
</ComingSoonRoomLayout>
